========
Overview
========
Simple project showing basic usage of the Akiban SQL Parser.

The demo, currently, will scan any valid SQL statement any print a referenced
column to stdout. This shows usage of the simplest way to consume a parsed
query tree, the com.akiban.sql.parser.Visitor interface.


==========
Dependency
==========
The parser is not yet in Maven Central so the easiest way to use it is to
manually install it in your local repository.

For example,
$ cd /tmp
$ wget https://launchpad.net/akiban-sql-parser/trunk/1.0.11/+download/akiban-sql-parser-1.0.11.tar.gz
$ tar xzf akiban-sql-parser-1.0.11.tar.gz
$ mvn install:install-file -Dfile=akiban-sql-parser-1.0.11/akiban-sql-parser-1.0.11.jar -DgroupId=com.akiban -DartifactId=akiban-sql-parser -Dversion=1.0.11 -Dpackaging=jar


=====
Build
=====
$ mvn package


=======
Running
=======
--------------------
Parse standard input
--------------------
$ echo "SELECT x FROM t" |java -jar target/ParserDemo.jar
Statement: CursorNode
  x

-----------------------------------------------
Run the internal demo and echo input statements
-----------------------------------------------
$ java -jar target/ParserDemo.jar --demo --echo
...

-------------------------------------------
Parse a file containing one or more queries
-------------------------------------------
$ java -jar target/ParserDemo.jar --file two_queries.sql 
Statement: CursorNode
  hello
Statement: InsertNode
  state
